<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="139" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="139">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Male</emphasis>
, wingspan 30 mm (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 7–12" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 7 - 12. Adults of Sacada spp. 7 S. unilinealis Hampson (male), India 8 S. unilinealis Hampson (male), holotype, Sikkim, India 9 S. inordinata (Walker) (male), holotype, Darjeeling, India 10 S. dzonguensis, sp. nov. (male), India. 11 S. umtasorensis, sp. nov. (male), India 12 S. pallescens Hampson (male), India. Scale bars: 5 mm (7, 10, 11); 12.7 mm (12)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.962.51194.figures7-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/443710" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">11</figureCitation>
). Rufous brown. Forewing with a sinuous medial fuscous line outwardly oblique from costa to vein Cu2, then broadly and inwardly rounded to meet inner margin; a band of paler scales on discocellular; postmedial fuscous line, slightly curved, inwardly oblique from costa to inner margin; inner area of medial line and outer area of postmedial line bordered with ochreous scales; a broad ferruginous band beyond postmedial line; a fine marginal line, cilia brownish; underside rufous with inner area ochreous. Hindwing pale fuscous with rufous tinge; traces of diffused, postmedial fuscous line; a fine marginal line present; underside rufous. 
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 27–32" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 27 - 32. Male genitalia of Sacada spp. 27, 28 Male genitalia of S. dzonguensis, sp. nov. 29, 30 male genitalia of S. umtasorensis, sp. nov. 31, 32 male genitalia of S. pallescens Hampson." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.962.51194.figures27-32" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/443713" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">29</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 27–32" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 27 - 32. Male genitalia of Sacada spp. 27, 28 Male genitalia of S. dzonguensis, sp. nov. 29, 30 male genitalia of S. umtasorensis, sp. nov. 31, 32 male genitalia of S. pallescens Hampson." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.962.51194.figures27-32" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/443713" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">30</figureCitation>
): uncus hooded with baso-lateral flaps; gnathos curved distally, hooked, tip pointed, broadened before tip; valva simple; transtilla broad with two apical, small thumb-like processes; juxta narrow, mediolateral area constricted, bifid apically with both the arms bearing spikes; vinculum U-shaped; aedeagus apex with single row of small spines; base of vesica densely scobinated and the scobination gradually becomes sparse towards apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="139" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="139">
<taxonomicName authorityName="N. Singh, Kirti &amp; Ranjan" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Sacada" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sacada umtasorensis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="umtasorensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Sacada umtasorensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., distributed in Meghalaya is most closely similar to its allopatric relative 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. dzonguensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" rank="species" species="dzonguensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">S. dzonguensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., (distributed in Sikkim) (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 7–12" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 7 - 12. Adults of Sacada spp. 7 S. unilinealis Hampson (male), India 8 S. unilinealis Hampson (male), holotype, Sikkim, India 9 S. inordinata (Walker) (male), holotype, Darjeeling, India 10 S. dzonguensis, sp. nov. (male), India. 11 S. umtasorensis, sp. nov. (male), India 12 S. pallescens Hampson (male), India. Scale bars: 5 mm (7, 10, 11); 12.7 mm (12)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.962.51194.figures7-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/443710" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">10</figureCitation>
), but it is distinct by the oblique postmedial line from costa to inner margin, whereas in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. dzonguensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" rank="species" species="dzonguensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">S. dzonguensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the postmedial line is straight from the costa to the radial vein and then oblique to the inner margin. In the male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. umtasorensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" rank="species" species="umtasorensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">S. umtasorensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 27–32" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 27 - 32. Male genitalia of Sacada spp. 27, 28 Male genitalia of S. dzonguensis, sp. nov. 29, 30 male genitalia of S. umtasorensis, sp. nov. 31, 32 male genitalia of S. pallescens Hampson." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.962.51194.figures27-32" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/443713" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">29</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 27–32" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 27 - 32. Male genitalia of Sacada spp. 27, 28 Male genitalia of S. dzonguensis, sp. nov. 29, 30 male genitalia of S. umtasorensis, sp. nov. 31, 32 male genitalia of S. pallescens Hampson." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.962.51194.figures27-32" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/443713" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">30</figureCitation>
), the juxta is narrow with the two apical lobes exhibiting more spines, and the aedeagus apex has a single row of small spines, whereas in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. dzonguensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" rank="species" species="dzonguensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">S. dzonguensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 27–32" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 27 - 32. Male genitalia of Sacada spp. 27, 28 Male genitalia of S. dzonguensis, sp. nov. 29, 30 male genitalia of S. umtasorensis, sp. nov. 31, 32 male genitalia of S. pallescens Hampson." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.962.51194.figures27-32" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/443713" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">27</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 27–32" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 27 - 32. Male genitalia of Sacada spp. 27, 28 Male genitalia of S. dzonguensis, sp. nov. 29, 30 male genitalia of S. umtasorensis, sp. nov. 31, 32 male genitalia of S. pallescens Hampson." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.962.51194.figures27-32" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/443713" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">28</figureCitation>
), the juxta is broad, the apical lobes have fewer spines, and the aedeagus apex exhibits multiple rows of small spines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
